### PHP Namespaces

Namespaces allow you to organize code and avoid name collisions with other developers' code.

### Declaring a Namespace

```php
<?php
namespace App\Models;

class User {
    public function __construct() {
        echo "User model from App\\Models";
    }
}
?>
```

### Using Namespaces

```php
<?php
// Import with use
use App\Models\User;

$user = new User(); // App\Models\User

// Fully qualified name
$user = new \App\Models\User();

// With alias
use App\Models\User as UserModel;
$user = new UserModel();
?>
```

### Multiple Namespaces in One File

```php
<?php
namespace App\Controllers {
    class HomeController {
        public function index() {
            echo "Home";
        }
    }
}

namespace App\Models {
    class User {
        public function getName() {
            return "John";
        }
    }
}
?>
```

### use Keyword

| Statement | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| `use \Namespace\Class;` | Import a class |
| `use \Namespace\Class as Alias;` | Import with alias |
| `use \Namespace\{ClassA, ClassB};` | Import multiple (PHP 7+) |
| `use function \Namespace\func;` | Import a function (PHP 5.6+) |
| `use const \Namespace\CONST;` | Import a constant (PHP 5.6+) |

### Global Namespace

```php
<?php
$date = new \DateTime(); // Uses global class
echo \strlen("Hello");    // Global function
?>
```

> **Key Point:** Namespaces are typically organized to match the directory structure (e.g., `App\Models\User` maps to `app/Models/User.php`).
